## Introduction

This report outlines the concept and initial Shopify setup for my practice store, **Little Legs Pet Co.**, a boutique pet store built around dachshunds and other small, long-bodied dog breeds. The store concept, target customer profile, and product plan below were developed as the foundation for the Shopify storefront setup completed in this assignment.

::: callout-note
This is a practice/prototype store created for coursework purposes only. No real payments are processed and no real transactions occur.
:::

## Store Name and Concept

**Store name:** Little Legs Pet Co.

**Concept:** Little Legs Pet Co. is a boutique e-commerce pet store that sells gear, apparel, treats, and accessories designed specifically for dachshunds and other small, long-bodied dog breeds. The store was inspired by my own two dachshunds and the gap I noticed in mainstream pet retail: most pet stores design products for an "average" dog body shape, which doesn't fit breeds with long backs and short legs well.

> "Most pet stores sell one-size-fits-most. Little Legs exists for the dogs that mainstream gear was never built for."

The store's brand identity leans playful and warm, using the dachshund's long, low silhouette as a recurring visual motif across packaging and the website.

## Target Customer

The target customer for Little Legs Pet Co. is a dachshund or small-breed dog owner who treats their pet as a family member and is willing to pay a premium for products designed specifically for their dog's body type and needs. Key characteristics include:

- **Demographics:** Primarily ages 25-45, skews female, urban and suburban households
- **Lifestyle:** Active on Instagram and TikTok pet content/communities; engaged in "pet parent" culture; likely to follow dachshund-specific accounts and influencers
- **Shopping behavior:** Shops online frequently, researches products before buying, values niche/specialty positioning over big-box pet retailers (e.g., Petco, Chewy)
- **Motivations:** Often concerned about breed-specific health issues such as Intervertebral Disc Disease (IVDD)[^1], which makes supportive, well-fitted gear especially appealing

[^1]: IVDD is a spinal condition common in long-bodied breeds like dachshunds, caused by degeneration of the discs between vertebrae. It is a major driver of demand for orthopedic and back-support pet products.

## Product Category Plan

Little Legs Pet Co. will launch with five core product categories, summarized in @tbl-categories below.

```{r}
#| label: tbl-categories
#| tbl-cap: "Little Legs Pet Co. - Initial Product Category Plan"
#| code-fold: true

categories <- data.frame(
  Category = c(
    "Orthopedic & Support Gear",
    "Apparel & Accessories",
    "Treats & Nutrition",
    "Toys & Enrichment",
    "Travel & Home Gear"
  ),
  `Example Products` = c(
    "Back-support harnesses, dog ramps, supportive dog beds",
    "Long-bodied sweaters, raincoats, custom-fit collars",
    "Joint-health treats, weight management chews",
    "Low-impact chew toys, puzzle feeders",
    "Low-clearance car seats, travel carriers, ramps for furniture"
  ),
  check.names = FALSE
)

knitr::kable(categories)
```

As shown in @tbl-categories, the product plan is intentionally anchored around the physical needs of long-bodied breeds rather than general pet merchandise, which is the core differentiator for this store concept.

